ally\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Will & Grace]]''<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| Aaron\n| Episode: \"The Birds & the Bees\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[What I Like About You (TV series)|What I Like About You]]''\n| Todd<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Descent (2005 film)|Descent]]''\n| Dr. Jake Rollins<ref name=\"Descent (2005)\">{{cite web |title=Descent (2005) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/v331212 |website=All Movie |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Supernova (2005 film)|Supernova]]''\n| Dr. Chris Richardson<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Windfall (TV series)|Windfall]]''\n| Peter Schaefer<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 13 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Biker Mice from Mars (2006 TV series)|Biker Mice from Mars]]''\n| Napoleon Brie (voice)<ref name=\"Biker Mice from Mars\">{{cite web |title=Biker Mice from Mars |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/biker-mice-from-mars/cast/ |website=TV.com |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Episode: \"Once Upon a Time on Earth\"\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[John from Cincinnati]]''\n| [[John from Cincinnati#Cast and characters|Linc Stark]]<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Noah Sibert<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n|Episode: \"Trials\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[A Gunfighter's Pledge]]''\n| Matt Austin<ref name=\"The Pledge (2008)\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[A Very Merry Daughter of the Bride]]''\n| Charlie<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2008;<br />2018\n| ''[[Criminal Minds]]''\n| Benjamin Cyrus<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The Storm (miniseries)|The Storm]]''\n| Stillman<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Angel and the Badman#Remake|Angel and the Badman]]''\n| Laredo Stevens<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''\n| Dalton Rand<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| Episode: \"The Future Job\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Generator Rex]]''\n| Jacob (voice)<ref name=\"Luke Perry - Behing the voice actors\" />\n| Episode: \"The Architect\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Fact Checkers Unit|FCU: Fact Checkers Unit]]''\n| Luke<ref name=\"Luke Perry on \u2018FCU: Fact Checkers Unit\u2019\">{{cite web |title=Luke Perry on \u2018FCU: Fact Checkers Unit\u2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodnews.com/2010/08/17/luke-perry-on-fcu-fact-checkers-unit/ |website=Hollywwod News |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Pound Puppies (2010 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]''\n| Fang (voice)<ref name=\"Luke Perry Dead: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know\">{{cite web |title=Luke Perry Dead: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/03/luke-perry-dead-dies-stroke/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Episode: \"Rebel Without a Collar\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Goodnight for Justice''\n| John Goodnight<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Goodnight for Justice: The Measure of a Man''\n| John Goodnight<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Goodnight for Justice: Queen of Hearts]]''\n| John Goodnight<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Raising Hope]]''\n| Ghost of Arbor Day<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| Episode: \"Arbor Daze\"\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[Body of Proof]]''\n| CDC Officer Dr. Charlie Stafford<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''\n| American Inspector Spacetime<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| Episode: \"Conventions of Space and Time\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Major Crimes (TV series)|Major Crimes]]''\n| Jon Worth<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| Episode: \"Cutting Loose\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Welcome Home''\n| Stewart Paylor<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Jesse Stone: Lost in Paradise]]''\n| Richard Steele<ref name=\"Jesse Stone: Lost in Paradise (2015)\">{{cite web |title=Jesse Stone: Lost in Paradise (2015) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/v646558 |website=All Movie |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Love in Paradise''\n| Avery Ford<ref name=\"TCM\" />\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Edge and Christian|The Edge and Christian Show That Totally Reeks of Awesomeness]]''\n| Himself<ref name=\"WWE Fans Leave Before Show Ends, 90210 Star On Edge And Christian's Show, Stephanie McMahon Workout\">{{cite web |last1=Middleton |first1=Marc |title=WWE Fans Leave Before Show Ends, 90210 Star On Edge And Christian's Show, Stephanie McMahon Workout |url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2016/02/wwe-fans-leave-before-show-ends-608108/ |website=Wrestling Inc |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Episode: \"The 90s\"\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''\n| [[Families of Archie's Gang#Fred Andrews|Fred Andrews]]<ref name=\"TV Guide\" />\n| 46 episodes\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist(s)\n! Role\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}} \n|-\n| 2009\n| \"[[\u00a1Happy Birthday Guadalupe!]]\"\n| [[The Killers]] featuring [[Wild Light]] and [[Mariachi El Bronx]]\n| The Cowboy\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=The Killers \u2013 \u00a1Happy Birthday Guadalupe! ft. Wild Light, Mariachi El Bronx|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C24KIIh_OzM|work=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{IMDb name|580}}\n*{{IBDB name|83374}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/197281602/luke-perry Luke Perry] on [[Find A Grave]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Luke}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Burials in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cerebrovascular disease]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Downey, California]]\n[[Category:People from Fredericktown, Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Huntington Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People from Mansfield, Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Paramount, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the American actor|the British industrial artist|Luke Perry (artist)|the Australian volleyball player|Luke Perry (volleyball)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Luke Perry\n| image              = Luke Perry by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Perry in July 2018\n| birth_name         = Coy Luther Perry III\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1966|10|11}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mansfield, Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|03|04|1966|10|11}}\n| death_place        = [[Burbank, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = <!--per the template documentation this parameter should not be included here-->\n| occupation         = {{Hlist|Actor|voice artist}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Rachel Sharp|1993|2003|end=divorced}}\n| children           = 2, including [[Jungle Boy (wrestler)|Jack]]\n| years active       = 1982\u20132019\n| television         = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''|''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''}}\n}}\n\n'''Coy Luther''' \"'''Luke'''\" '''Perry III''' (October 11, 1966&nbsp;\u2013 March 4, 2019) was an American actor. He became a teen idol for playing [[Dylan McKay]] on the TV series ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'' from 1990 to 1995, and again from 1998 to 2000. He also starred as [[Families of Archie's Gang#Fred Andrews|Fred Andrews]] on the [[The CW|CW]] series ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'', had guest roles on notable shows such as ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', ''[[The Simpsons]]'', and ''[[Will & Grace]]'', and also starred in several films, including ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' (1992), ''[[8 Seconds]]'' (1994), ''[[The Fifth Element]]'' (1997), and ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]'' (2019), his final feature performance.\n\n==Early life==\nLuke Perry was born on October 11, 1966 in [[Mansfield, Ohio|Mansfield]], [[Ohio]],<ref name=\"James Brady\">{{cite magazine |author=James Brady |title=In Step With... Luke Perry |magazine=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |date=June 25, 2006 |url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/2006/edition_06-25-2006/In_Step_With |access-date=July 15, 2007 }}</ref> the second of three children to Ann Perry, a homemaker, and Coy Luther Perry Jr., a steelworker.<ref name=\"James Brady\"/> His parents divorced in 1972,<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = March 5, 2019 | date= March 4, 2019 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/04/arts/luke-perry-dead.html| title = Luke Perry, \u2018Beverly Hills, 90210\u2019 Star, Is Dead at 52 | first = Neil | last= Genzlinger | first2=Elizabeth A. | last2 = Harris}}</ref> and his mother later married Steve Bennett, a construction worker, with whom she had another child. His biological father died of a heart attack in 1980.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/luke-perry-20810855|title=Luke Perry|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref> Perry was raised in [[Fredericktown, Ohio]], and played Freddie Bird, the school mascot for [[Fredericktown High School]].<ref name=\"Luke Perry Is Dead at 52\">{{cite web |title=Luke Perry Is Dead at 52 |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/luke-perry-obituary |website=Vogue |access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Beginnings===\nIn 1984, Perry moved to [[Los Angeles]] shortly after high school to pursue acting.<ref name=\":0\" /> He worked odd jobs, including for an [[asphalt]] paving company and in a [[doorknob]] factory.<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite interview|last=Perry|first=Luke|interviewer=Julia Keller|title=From the archives: A conversation with Ohioan Luke Perry, who stars in \u2018Beverly Hills\u2019 90210|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20190304/from-archives-conversation-with-ohioan-luke-perry-who-stars-in-beverly-hills-90210|access-date=March 4, 2019|work=Columbus Dispatch|date=November 8, 1990}}</ref> He appeared in the 1985 music video of \"[[Be Chrool to Your Scuel]]\" for the band [[Twisted Sister]], and by 1988, Perry had auditioned for 256 acting jobs before receiving his first acceptance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/04/us/luke-perry-dies/index.html|title=Luke Perry, star of 'Beverly Hills 90210' and 'Riverdale,' dead at 52|last1=Respers France|first1=Lisa|date=March 4, 2019|website=cnn.com|publisher=CNN|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> After moving to New York, Perry's earliest roles were on daytime soap operas: one episode of ''[[Loving (TV series)|Loving]]'' (1987\u20131988) and ten episodes of ''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'' (1988\u20131989).<ref name=\"Remembering Luke Perry: Photos from the Actor's Career Before '90210'\">{{cite web |last1=Elliott |first1=Megan |title=Remembering Luke Perry: Photos from the Actor's Career Before '90210' |url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/remembering-luke-perry-photos-from-the-actors-career-before-90210.html/ |website=CheatSheet |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Rise to fame: ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' era===\nIn 1989, Perry got the role of the brooding millionaire's son [[Dylan McKay]] on Fox's [[teen drama]] ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He originally auditioned for the role of [[List of Beverly Hills, 90210 characters#Steve Sanders|Steve Sanders]], but lost to [[Ian Ziering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/1020503/how-beverly-hills-90210-made-luke-perry-a-brooding-heartthrob-for-the-ages|title=How Beverly Hills, 90210 Made Luke Perry a Brooding Heartthrob for the Ages|date=March 4, 2019|website=E! News|accessdate=2019-05-06}}</ref> With this role, Perry became a popular [[teen idol]]; a riot broke out when 10,000 teen girls attended an August 1991 autograph session at [[Plantation Walk|The Fashion Mall at Plantation]], causing him to leave after 90 seconds.<ref name=\"ss19910811\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1991-08-11-9101300695-story.html |title=Melee at the Broward mall: 20 injured during surge for heartthrob Luke Perry {{!}} From the archives |last=Delgado |first=Berta |date=August 11, 1991 |work=Sun-Sentinel |access-date=March 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://outline.com/pUTyju |archive-date=March 4, 2019 |url-status=live |last2=Doup |first2=Liz |language=en-US}}</ref> While starring in ''90210'', Perry won a supporting role in the original film version of [[Joss Whedon]]'s ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)|Buffy The Vampire Slayer]]'' (1992).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://calgaryherald.com/entertainment/local-arts/calgary-comic-expo-luke-perry-talks-about-buffy-the-vampire-slayer-shooting-in-alberta-and-the-three-dimensional-dylan-mckay|title=Calgary Comic Expo: Luke Perry talks about Buffy the Vampire Slayer|last=Perry|first=Luke|date=March 20, 2015|newspaper=[[Calgary Herald]]|access-date=March 5, 2019|type=Interview|interviewer=Eric Volmers}}</ref> He also starred in ''[[Terminal Bliss]]'' in 1992,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunter|first=Stephen|author-link=Stephen Hunter|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1992-03-10-1992070098-story.html|title=Luke Perry gropes for 'Terminal Bliss'|date=March 10, 1992|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> and as [[Lane Frost]] in ''[[8 Seconds]]'' in 1994.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Mooney|first=Thomas|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/luke-perry-8-seconds-rodeo-lane-frost-803172/|title=How Luke Perry's Rodeo Movie '8 Seconds' Illuminated Life Outside the 90210|date=March 4, 2019|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an attempt to find more mature roles, he decided to leave ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' in 1995. That year, he took a part in the Italian film ''Vacanze di Natale '95'', playing himself. Although he announced that ''90210'' was behind him, his absence lasted for only three years, and he returned to the show in 1998. During this time, Perry starred in the independent film ''[[Normal Life]]'' opposite [[Ashley Judd]],<ref name=\"Normal Life (1996)\">{{cite web |title=Normal Life (1996) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/normal_life/ |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> starred in the TV science fiction movie ''[[Invasion (miniseries)|Invasion]]'' (1997),<ref name=\"Invasion (1997)\">{{cite web |title=Invasion (1997) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/invasion-v258643/cast-crew |website=All Movie |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Riot (1997 film)|Riot]]'' (1997), a drama about the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]].<ref name=\"Riot in the Streets (1997)\">{{cite web |title=Riot in the Streets (1997) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/v176577 |website=All Movie |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> He had a small role in [[Luc Besson]]'s science fiction adventure film ''[[The Fifth Element]]'' (1997). In 1998, he returned to ''90210'', where he remained as a permanent special guest star through the show's final season in 2000.<ref name=\"Luke Perry Is Dead at 52\" /> In 1999, he starred in the film ''[[Storm (1999 film)|Storm]].''\n\nHe said of his role on ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' as Dylan McKay: \"I'm going to be linked with him until I die, but that's actually just fine. I created Dylan McKay. He's mine,\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Luke Perry shooting new film in Sweden |url=https://www.upi.com/Luke-Perry-shooting-new-film-in-Sweden/95841221487418/ |website=upi.com |publisher=UPI |date=September 15, 2008|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> but did not reprise his role in the spin-off. He stated: \"When you're in the professional acting business, you have to look into all these offers, and I don't mean anything bad about it but creatively it's something I have done before and I don't know how it will benefit me if I do it again.\"<ref>{{cite news | work= TV Guide | date= September 18, 2008 | access-date = March 5, 2019| title = Luke Perry Holding Firm with His 9021-'No' | url = https://www.tvguide.com/news/luke-perry-holding-17567/}}</ref> Perry said the fact that the show's longtime producer [[Aaron Spelling]] was not involved in the revival was critical: \"The difference between CW bringing something back and Aaron Spelling doing something is significant. And I cannot do it without Aaron.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Luchina |title='Beverly Hills, 90210': Where Are They Now?|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/beverly-hills-90210-now/story?id=11428888|website=abcnews.go.com |publisher=ABC News |date=August 19, 2010|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> However, [[Shannen Doherty]], [[Jennie Garth]], and [[Tori Spelling]] reprised their roles in the [[90210 (TV series)|2008 revival of the series]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Jennie Garth|date=2019-04-09|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Jennie_Garth&oldid=891607183|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n===Later work===\nFrom 2001 to 2002, he starred in the HBO prison drama ''[[Oz (TV series)|Oz]]'', as the Reverend [[List of Oz (TV series) characters#Christian inmates|Jeremiah Cloutier]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edgerton|first1=Gary R.|last2=Jones|first2=Jeffery P.|author2-link=Jeffrey P. Jones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THEE7TZRAN0C&pg=PT64|title=The Essential HBO Reader|page=64|year=2013|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|isbn=978-0-8131-4372-9|via=[[Google Books]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> From 2002 to 2004 he starred in the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] television series ''[[Jeremiah (TV series)|Jeremiah]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Garcia|first1=Frank|last2=Phillips|first2=Mark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQIDAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA135|title=Science Fiction Television Series, 1990-2004:Histories, Casts and Credits for 58 Shows|page=135|year=2013|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-0-7864-9183-4|via=Google Books|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> Perry went on to star in a 2002 [[Television film|television movie]] called ''[[The Triangle (film)|The Triangle]]''.<ref name=\"The Triangle\">{{cite web |last1=Speier |first1=Michael |title=The Triangle |url=https://variety.com/2001/tv/reviews/the-triangle-2-1200469554/ |website=Variety |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In 2006, Perry co-starred in the ensemble drama series ''[[Windfall (TV series)|Windfall]]'', about a group of friends who win the lottery. The series ran for 13 episodes during the summer of 2006 on [[NBC]].<ref name=\"Remembering Luke Perry: Photos from the Actor's Career Before '90210'\" /> In 2007, he landed the role of Tommy \"Santa\" Santorelli on the film ''[[The Sandlot: Heading Home]]'', and he appeared in the 2008 [[Western (genre)|western]] ''[[A Gunfighter's Pledge]]''.<ref name=\"The Pledge (2008)\">{{cite web |title=The Pledge (2008) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/v449633 |website=All Movie |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Sandlot: Heading Home\">{{cite web |title=The Sandlot: Heading Home |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/sandlot_heading_home |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> Perry also appeared in the 2007 [[HBO]] series ''[[John from Cincinnati]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Lowry|first=Brian|url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/john-from-cincinnati-1200558770/|title=John From Cincinnati|date=June 6, 2007|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> He also starred in the Swedish film ''\u00c4ntligen Midsommar'' (''Finally Midsummer''), which was released in the summer of 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Oz-Gun|first=Theresa|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20091001/22388|title=Luke Perry: from 90s teen hearthrob to Swedish film star|date=October 1, 2009|newspaper=[[The Local]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPerry did considerable voice-over work for various animated series, usually playing himself. He played himself (as [[Krusty the Clown]]'s half brother) in \"[[Krusty Gets Kancelled]]\", an episode of ''The Simpsons'' (1993).<ref name=\"A Star is Burns / 4 Jan 2010 2:43 PM PST Top 25 Simpsons Guest Appearances\">{{cite web |title=A Star is Burns / 4 Jan 2010 2:43 PM PST Top 25 Simpsons Guest Appearances |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2010/01/04/top-25-simpsons-guest-appearances?page=5 |website=IGN |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> He voiced himself in an episode of ''[[Johnny Bravo]]'', giving Johnny dating advice after Johnny saved him from a stampede of fan girls. Perry parodied himself in \"[[The Story on Page One]]\", an episode of ''[[Family Guy]]'', in which he sues [[Peter Griffin]] for calling him [[gay]] in a newspaper article.<ref name=\"The Story on Page One\">{{cite web |title=The Story on Page One |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/family-guy/the-story-on-page-one-25466/ |website=TV.com |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> His other voice work includes ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1996 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]'', ''[[Biker Mice from Mars]]'', ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'', and ''[[The Night of the Headless Horseman]]''.<ref name=\"Luke Perry - Behing the voice actors\">{{cite web |title=Luke Perry |url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Luke-Perry/ |website=Behing the voice actors |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Remembering Luke Perry: Photos from the Actor's Career Before '90210'\" />\n\nPerry guest-starred as gay characters in the sitcoms ''[[Spin City]]'' (1997) and ''[[Will & Grace]]'' (2005); in the former, he appeared as Carter Heywood's ex-boyfriend who subsequently fell in love with a woman, and in the latter he played a geeky [[Birdwatching|birdwatcher]] who catches the eye of [[Jack McFarland]].<ref name=\"'Riverdale' star Luke Perry has died at the age of 52\">{{cite web |title='Riverdale' star Luke Perry has died at the age of 52 |url=https://www.attitude.co.uk/article/riverdale-star-luke-perry-has-died-at-the-age-of-52-1/20430/ |website=Attitude.co.uk |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In 2005, Perry was reunited with former ''90210'' co-star [[Jennie Garth]] when he guest-starred on ''[[What I Like About You (TV series)|What I Like About You]]'' in a loose parody of their ''90210'' characters' relationship.<ref name=\"What I Like About You\">{{cite web |title=What I Like About You |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/what-i-like-about-you/cast/ |website=TV.com |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In 2008, Perry guest-starred as rapist Noah Sibert in the season premiere of the television series ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theinsider.com/news/1100294_Luke_Perry_to_Guest_on_Law_Order_SVU |title=Luke Perry to Guest on \"Law & Order: SVU\" |last= |first= |date=July 30, 2008 |publisher=[[The Insider (TV program)|The Insider]] |access-date=May 20, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731101031/http://www.theinsider.com/news/1100294_Luke_Perry_to_Guest_on_Law_Order_SVU |archivedate=July 31, 2009 |df=}}</ref> He also guest-starred as cult leader Benjamin Cyrus in an episode of ''Criminal Minds''. In late 2009, Perry starred in [[The Killers]]' music video for their fourth annual Christmas single, \"[[\u00a1Happy Birthday Guadalupe!]]\".<ref name=\"Happy Birthday Guadalupe\">{{cite web |title=Happy Birthday Guadalupe |url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/the-killers/happy-birthday-guadalupe |website=Song Facts |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe same year, Perry participated in the [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson's]] audio Bible production known as ''The Word of Promise''. In this dramatized audio, Perry played both [[Saint Stephen]] and [[Judas Iscariot]]. The project also featured a large ensemble of other well-known Hollywood actors, including [[Jim Caviezel]], [[Louis Gossett Jr.]], [[John Rhys-Davies]], [[Jon Voight]], [[Gary Sinise]], [[Jason Alexander]], [[Christopher McDonald]], [[Marisa Tomei]], [[Stacy Keach]] and [[John Schneider (screen actor)|John Schneider]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.thewordofpromise.com/MeetTheCast.aspx |website= Thomas Nelson Publishers| title=The Word of Promise: Cast |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date= November 16, 2009 | access-date= March 4, 2019 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/16/local/me-beliefs16 |work= Los Angeles Times | title=BELIEFS: Stars lined up for elaborate audio Bible : Michael York, Jason Alexander and many others gave voice to a 79-CD reading of Old and New Testaments}}</ref>\n\nPerry appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2001 in a revival of ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'', playing Brad Majors.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen M.|last=Silverman|authorlink=Stephen M. Silverman|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,622159,00.html |title=From 90210 to 10036: Perry on B'way |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City |date=June 29, 2001|access-date=July 1, 2007}}</ref> In 2004, he appeared in the [[London]] production of ''[[When Harry Met Sally...#Legacy|When Harry Met Sally&nbsp;...]]'' as Harry, alongside [[Alyson Hannigan]] as Sally.<ref>{{cite magazine |first1=Anne|last1=Hansford|first2=Stephen M.|last2=Silverman|authorlink2=Stephen M. Silverman|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,26334,627429,00.html |title=Hannigan Orgasmic over New Stage Role |access-date=July 1, 2007 |date=January 8, 2004 |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001044558/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,26334,627429,00.html |archivedate=October 1, 2007 |df=}}</ref> He played a con man/psychic in a second-season episode of ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]'' in 2010,<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawidziak|first=Mark|author-link=Mark Dawidziak|url=https://www.cleveland.com/tv-blog/index.ssf/2010/01/mansfield_native_luke_perry_guest_stars_on_tnts_leverage.html|title=Mansfield native Luke Perry guest stars on TNT's 'Leverage'|date=January 29, 2010|newspaper=[[The Plain Dealer]]|via=[[Advance Digital|Cleveland.com]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> and then appeared as the American version of [[List of Doctor Who parodies#Community (2011)|Inspector Spacetime]] in an episode of ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' in 2013, titled \"[[Biology 101]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes|first=Jason|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/22/community-luke-perry-jennie-garth-video_n_2738960.html|title='Community' Stages '90210' Reunion As Luke Perry And Jennie Garth Star In Pierce's Version Of 'Inspector Spacetime' (VIDEO)|date=February 22, 2013|website=[[HuffPost|The Huffington Post]]|access-date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2017 until his death, Perry starred as Frederick \"Fred\" Andrews, [[Archie Andrews|Archie's]] father and owner of Andrews Construction, on the [[The CW|CW]] series ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]''.<ref name=\"Luke Perry Is Dead at 52\" /> Starting with \"Chapter Forty-Nine: Fire Walk with Me\", the first episode to air following his death, all new episodes of the series would be dedicated to him.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1103326251723489285|title=Going through pictures on my way to set. From the early days. With Luke in the middle. Our heart, always. Tonight\u2019s episode of #Riverdale\u2060 \u2060 finds Fred doing what he does best--helping Archie. It is dedicated to Luke, as all episodes will be for the rest of our run.rat=Roberto|last=Aguirre-Sacasa|user=writerRAS|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> He played Canadian actor [[Wayne Maunder]] in the 2019 film ''[[Once Upon a Time in Hollywood]]'', about 1960s Hollywood around the time of the [[Charles Manson]] [[Tate murders|murders]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/04/luke-perry-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/|title=Luke Perry's final role will be in Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref> Directed by [[Quentin Tarantino]], it was Perry's final film role.\n\n==Personal life==\nPerry married Rachel Minnie Sharp on November 20, 1993 in Beverly Hills.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gliatto |first1=Tom |title=The Luke of Love |url=https://people.com/archive/the-luke-of-love-vol-40-no-23/ |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=December 6, 1993|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> They separated in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/45069/luke-perry-splitsville-90210|title=Luke Perry: Splitsville, 90210|date=May 4, 2003|publisher=[[E! News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.sfgate.com/dailydish/2012/08/16/jennie-garth-turns-to-luke-perry-for-post-split-support/|title=Jennie Garth turns to Luke Perry for post-split support| date=August 16, 2012|website=Daily Dish}}</ref> and they had two children, son [[Jungle Boy (wrestler)|Jack Perry]] (born June 16, 1997) and daughter Sophie Perry (born June 7, 2000).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/765363/A-baby-girl-joins-Luke-Perry-wife.html|title=A baby girl joins Luke Perry, wife|date=June 10, 2000|work=[[Deseret News]]|archivedate=October 13, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013013651/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/765363/A-baby-girl-joins-Luke-Perry-wife.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/luke-perry-would-never-let-his-daughter-date-dylan-mckay-t108856|title=Luke Perry reveals why he'd never let his daughter date Dylan McKay|work=[[Today (US TV show)|Today]]| date= March 3, 2017 | access-date = March 4, 2019 | first = Gina | last = Vivinetto}}</ref> Jack Perry is a professional wrestler known by his ring name Jungle Boy, and is signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/822564/luke-perry-supports-his-son-jungle-boy-nate-coy-at-a-wrestling-tournament|title=Luke Perry Supports His Son Jungle Boy at Wrestling Match|date=January 17, 2017|website=E! Online}}</ref> Perry became an advocate for [[colorectal cancer]] testing after undergoing a [[colonoscopy]] in 2015 that revealed pre-cancerous growths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/90210-actor-luke-perry-opens-up-about-2015-cancer-scare|title='90210' actor Luke Perry opens up about 2015 cancer scare|first=Lindsay|last=Carlton|date=March 17, 2017|website=Fox News}}</ref> As a result of the scare, he created a will naming his children as the sole beneficiaries.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trialandheirs/2019/03/08/luke-perry-estate-planning/|title=Luke Perry Protected His Family With Estate Planning|last=Mayoras|first=Danielle and Andy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref> At the time of his death, Perry was engaged<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aol.com/article/entertainment/2019/03/06/luke-perry-was-secretly-engaged-before-his-death-all-about-fiancee-wendy/23685729/|title=Luke Perry was secretly engaged before his death: Who is his fianc\u00e9e, Wendy?|website=AOL|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ring>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/luke-perrys-fiancee-spotted-wearing-her-engagement-ring-after-his-death/|title=Luke Perry's Fiancee Is Spotted Wearing Her Engagement Ring|date=2019-03-09|website=Us Weekly|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref> to Wendy Madison Bauer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/588875da2495485da3de16e873ffb7a8|title=Luke Perry, heartthrob on '90210,' dies at 52 after stroke|last=Elber|first=Lynn|date=March 4, 2019|website=AP NEWS|accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-47448666|title=Actor Luke Perry dies after stroke at 52|date=March 4, 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> a therapist and former part-time actress.<ref name=Ring/>\n\n==Death==\nPerry suffered a massive [[ischemic stroke]] at his home in [[Sherman Oaks, Los Angeles]] on February 27, 2019. After a second stroke, his family made the decision to remove him from life support,<ref name=\":1\" /> and he died on March 4 at age 52.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/obituaries-people-news/luke-perry-dead-dies-90210-riverdale-1203154263|title=Luke Perry, '90210' and 'Riverdale' Star, Dies at 52|last=Thorne|first=Will|date=March 4, 2019 |work=Variety |access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> He was buried near his home in [[VanLeer, Tennessee|Vanleer, Tennessee]], where he had a farm and had lived since 1995. In the aftermath of his death, the [[Reelz]] channel announced a documentary titled ''Luke Perry: In His Own Words.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reelz.com/luke-perry-words/|title=Luke Perry: In His Own Words|website=REELZChannel|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> As a result of his death, his ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' character Fred Andrews also died and the fourth season premiere was a tribute episode dedicated to him and his character. All future episodes were to be dedicated in his memory.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Scorchers (film)|Scorchers]]''<ref name=Dispatch/>\n| Ray Ray\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Terminal Bliss]]''<ref name=\"Dispatch\"/>\n| John Hunter\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/celebrities-who-died-in-2019/|title=From Katherine Helmond to Carol Channing: Remembering the Stars We've Lost in 2019|work=People| date=March 1, 2019 | first =Kate | last= Hogan 