{"title_page": "Hercules Stewart", "text_new": "'''Hercules Stewart of Whitelaw''' (died 1595) was a Scottish landowner and outlaw supporter of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]].\n\nHercules Stewart was a half-brother of Francis Stewart, 5th [[Earl of Bothwell]]. He was a son of John Stewart, Prior of [[Coldingham]] (d. 1563), who was an illegitimate son of [[James V of Scotland]] by his mistress Elizabeth Carmichael.\n\nHercules Stewart supported his brother, the rebel earl, against [[James VI of Scotland]].\n\nIn 1591 Stewart and the younger Hamilton of Samuelston executed a man called Purdy without trial.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 625, 642, 807.</ref>\n\nIn March 1592 he was thought to be in hiding in [[Northumberland]] with the earl, the Laird of Niddry, and others who had tried to access the king's presence by force at [[Holyroodhouse]]. In June 1592 he was declared guilty of treason in the [[Parliament of Scotland]]. In November 1592 Hercules and a number of Bothwell's supporters, including [[John Wemyss of Logie]], were pardoned for their treasons.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 650, 687, 818, 821.</ref>\n\nIn April 1594 Bothwell's supporters dug in at [[Leith]], repairing the old fortifications. They withdrew to [[Niddrie, Edinburgh|Niddrie]] where, on 5 April 1594 Hercules Stewart was given command of a section of Bothwell's troops and fought and defeated the king's soldiers under the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]] and the [[Alexander Home, 1st Earl of Home|Earl of Home]], who split into two groups and retreated towards [[Edinburgh Castle]] and [[Holyroodhouse]]. This engagement is sometimes known as the \"Battle of Leith\".<ref>Annie Isabella Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 305 no. 238.</ref>\n\nHercules Stewart wrote letters for the Earl of Bothwell, although the English agent [[George Nicholson (diplomat)|George Nicholson]] and the courtier [[Roger Aston]] suggested that Hercules Stewart was not in the earl's confidence.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 395 no. 307, 536 no. 472.</ref>\n\nStewart was denounced by the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] for conspiracy with Bothwell on 9 January 1595. The other conspirators were [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie|Alexander, Lord Spynie]], Archibald Wauchope younger of Niddry, Gilbert Pennycuke, William Chirnsyde, Sym Armstrong of Whitehaugh, and Josias Stewart, brother of [[Andrew Stuart, 1st Baron Castle Stuart|Andrew, Lord Ochiltree]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1882), p. 114., Spynie, Wauchope, and Pennycuke were denounced on 27 December 1594.</ref> Josias's [[Margaret Stewart, Mistress of Ochiltree|mother and sisters]] were ladies in waiting to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>Michael Pearce, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14629712.2019.1626110 'Anna of Denmark: Fashioning a Danish Court in Scotland', ''The Court Historian'', 24:2 (2019) pp. 146-8].</ref> \n\nStewart and William Trotter were captured by William Hume on 6 February 1595 at West Houses near Newbattle who tried to get him pardoned. It was suspected that Trotter incriminated Stewart. [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]] was at the arrest, and promised that he would be spared.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 530-1 & fn, 534, 536.</ref> Hercules and Josias Stewart was interrogated and revealed information about a band or league between Bothwell and the Catholic rebel Northern earls.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1882), p. 207.</ref>\n\nStewart and a man called Sym (Sym Armstrong, younger of Whitehaugh) were hanged on 18 February 1595 in the market place of Edinburgh.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 536 no. 472, 538 no. 474.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHercules married Mary Whitelaw, daughter and heir of Patrick Whitelaw of Whitelaw. They were divorced in 1592 and she married William Hume, who worked in the king's stable.\n\nThey had a daughter, Margaret Stewart. In 1620, a French woman, Jacqueline Quenlie, petitioned the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] that John Hamilton of Ferguslie was her husband in Ireland, and he had married Margaret Stewart unlawfully and taken two coffers of her belongings to Paisley. Jacqueline then withdrew her claim to the wife of John Hamilton and received her goods.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1619-1622'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1895), pp. 207-8, 209: ''Original Letters Relating to the Ecclesiastical Affairs of Scotland: 1614-1625'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1851), pp. 603-5.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Hercules}}\n[[Category:1595 deaths]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Kingdom of Scotland by hanging]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hercules Stewart of Whitelaw''' (died 1595) was a Scottish landowner and outlaw supporter of [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]].\n\nHercules Stewart was a half-brother of Francis Stewart, 5th [[Earl of Bothwell]]. He was a son of John Stewart, Prior of [[Coldingham]] (d. 1563), who was an illegitimate son of [[James V of Scotland]] by his mistress Elizabeth Carmichael.\n\nHercules Stewart supported his brother, the rebel earl, against [[James VI of Scotland]].\n\nIn 1591 Stewart and the younger Hamilton of Samuelston executed a man called Purdy without trial.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1585-1592'', vol. 4 (Edinburgh, 1881), pp. 625, 642, 807.</ref>\n\nIn March 1592 he was thought to be in hiding in [[Northumberland]] with the earl, the Laird of Niddry, and others who had tried to access the king's presence by force at [[Holyroodhouse]]. In June 1592 he was declared guilty of treason in the [[Parliament of Scotland]]. In November 1592 Hercules and a number of Bothwell's supporters, including [[John Wemyss of Logie]], were pardoned for their treasons.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 650, 687, 818, 821.</ref>\n\nIn April 1594 Bothwell's supporters dug in at [[Leith]], repairing the old fortifications. They withdrew to [[Niddrie, Edinburgh|Niddrie]] where, on 5 April 1594 Hercules Stewart was given command of a section of Bothwell's troops and fought and defeated the king's soldiers under the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]] and the [[Alexander Home, 1st Earl of Home|Earl of Home]], who split into two groups and retreated towards [[Edinburgh Castle]] and [[Holyroodhouse]]. This engagement is sometimes known as the \"Battle of Leith\".<ref>Annie Isabella Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 305 no. 238.</ref>\n\nHercules Stewart wrote letters for the Earl of Bothwell, although the English agent George Nicholson and the courtier [[Roger Aston]] suggested that Hercules Stewart was not in the earl's confidence.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 395 no. 307, 536 no. 472.</ref>\n\nStewart was denounced by the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] for conspiracy with Bothwell on 9 January 1595. The other conspirators were [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie|Alexander, Lord Spynie]], Archibald Wauchope younger of Niddry, Gilbert Pennycuke, William Chirnsyde, Sym Armstrong of Whitehaugh, and Josias Stewart, brother of [[Andrew Stuart, 1st Baron Castle Stuart|Andrew, Lord Ochiltree]].<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1882), p. 114., Spynie, Wauchope, and Pennycuke were denounced on 27 December 1594.</ref> Josias's [[Margaret Stewart, Mistress of Ochiltree|mother and sisters]] were ladies in waiting to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>Michael Pearce, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14629712.2019.1626110 'Anna of Denmark: Fashioning a Danish Court in Scotland', ''The Court Historian'', 24:2 (2019) pp. 146-8].</ref> \n\nStewart and William Trotter were captured by William Hume on 6 February 1595 at West Houses near Newbattle who tried to get him pardoned. It was suspected that Trotter incriminated Stewart. [[John Colville (c. 1540\u20131605)|John Colville]] was at the arrest, and promised that he would be spared.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 530-1 & fn, 534, 536.</ref> Hercules and Josias Stewart was interrogated and revealed information about a band or league between Bothwell and the Catholic rebel Northern earls.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1882), p. 207.</ref>\n\nStewart and a man called Sym (Sym Armstrong, younger of Whitehaugh) were hanged on 18 February 1595 in the market place of Edinburgh.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 536 no. 472, 538 no. 474.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHercules married Mary Whitelaw, daughter and heir of Patrick Whitelaw of Whitelaw. They were divorced in 1592 and she married William Hume, who worked in the king's stable.\n\nThey had a daughter, Margaret Stewart. In 1620, a French woman, Jacqueline Quenlie, petitioned the [[Privy Council of Scotland]] that John Hamilton of Ferguslie was her husband in Ireland, and he had married Margaret Stewart unlawfully and taken two coffers of her belongings to Paisley. Jacqueline then withdrew her claim to the wife of John Hamilton and received her goods.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1619-1622'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1895), pp. 207-8, 209: ''Original Letters Relating to the Ecclesiastical Affairs of Scotland: 1614-1625'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1851), pp. 603-5.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Hercules}}\n[[Category:1595 deaths]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Kingdom of Scotland by hanging]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hercules_Stewart"}
